00:01:11.880 --> 00:01:16.240
People say the land of Cantor Gwelod lies far below the sea in Cardigan Bay.

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:23.240
They say that in the Middle Ages it was a marshy land that ran beside the coast with gates to keep out the sea.

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:28.240
The King of Cantor Gwelod appointed a man called Saith Ennin to shut the gates at high tide.

00:01:28.240 --> 00:01:31.240
And open them again at low tide.

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:33.240
But Saith Ennin was a drunk.

00:01:33.240 --> 00:01:39.240
So one day he forgot to shut the gates and the sea came in and drowned the land.

00:01:39.240 --> 00:01:43.240
But we know another much older version of this story.

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:45.240
Which we're going to tell you now.

00:01:45.240 --> 00:01:48.240
With a bit of our own embroidery.

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:52.240
After all, that's what you do with legends, isn't it?

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:54.240
You change them.

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:58.240
In this version of the legend, the daughter of the King is called Mererid.

00:01:58.240 --> 00:02:00.240
